{"id": "51267", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51267", "title": "Tomb of Rakkis", "text": "The Tomb of Rakkis is the burial site of King &lt;a href=\"Rakkis\"&gt;Rakkis&lt;/a&gt;, located in the &lt;a href=\"Ruins%20of%20Corvus\"&gt;Ruins of Corvus&lt;/a&gt; below the &lt;a href=\"Blood%20Marsh\"&gt;Blood Marsh&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Westmarch\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt;. The location of the Tomb was unknown to most humans, according to &lt;a href=\"Diadra%20the%20Scholar\"&gt;Diadra the Scholar&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt; and the New &lt;a href=\"Horadrim\"&gt;Horadrim&lt;/a&gt; attempted to hide the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Soulstone\"&gt;Black Soulstone&lt;/a&gt; there after &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;'s defeat, but &lt;a href=\"Malthael\"&gt;Malthael&lt;/a&gt; attacked them and took the stone for himself.\nThe Tomb is not accessible during gameplay, but is depicted in the opening &lt;a href=\"cutscene\"&gt;cutscene&lt;/a&gt; of \"\"."}
{"id": "25690", "revid": "5562046", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=25690", "title": "Tomb of Sardar", "text": "The Tomb of Sardar is found in &lt;a href=\"Act%20II%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Act II&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", at the northern end of the &lt;a href=\"Dahlgur%20Oasis\"&gt;Dahlgur Oasis&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Tomes\"&gt;lorebook&lt;/a&gt; titled \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Musings%20of%20Sardar\"&gt;The Musings of Sardar&lt;/a&gt;\" is present, which is required for the &lt;a href=\"Judge%20of%20Character\"&gt;Judge of Character&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"achievements\"&gt;achievement&lt;/a&gt;.\nInside, the &lt;a href=\"Sardar%27s%20Treasure\"&gt;Sardar's Treasure&lt;/a&gt; event starts, and &lt;a href=\"Sardar\"&gt;Sardar&lt;/a&gt; himself can be found in the end of the dungeon (in his &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt; form).\nTo open the doors (both entrance and the vault), player(s) must find and turn the two levers: one outside the cave and one in its farthest end."}
