{"id": "3056", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3056", "title": "Trading", "text": "Trading is the act of giving and/or receiving items between two players, or between a player and an &lt;a href=\"NPCs\"&gt;NPC&lt;/a&gt;. Giving an item without something in return\u00a0or getting an item without offering something yourself is also called trading.\nDiablo II.\nWhen trading with other players, &lt;a href=\"gold\"&gt;gold&lt;/a&gt; is rarely used as a currency. In \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\"\u00a0runes, gear, charms, and jewels are the most commonly traded items between players. The most common currency is often runes, as these usually have a fixed value and are necessary for some of the most powerful equipment in the game.\nDiablo III.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", trading was fully implemented in the vanilla game (both personal trade and &lt;a href=\"Auction%20House\"&gt;Auction House&lt;/a&gt;), but with most, if not all decent items becoming &lt;a href=\"Account%20Bound\"&gt;Account Bound&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Reaper%20of%20Souls\"&gt;Reaper of Souls&lt;/a&gt;\", the trade between players has mostly become obsolete. &lt;a href=\"Gold\"&gt;Gold&lt;/a&gt; also cannot be transferred anymore.\nDiablo IV.\nTrading returns in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\". Legendary and Unique items cannot be traded, nor can items that have been enchanted by &lt;a href=\"the%20Occultist\"&gt;the Occultist&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "41734", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=41734", "title": "Trading at the Market", "text": "Trading at the Market is the twelfth &lt;a href=\"Westmarch%20%28City%29\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\". It follows on directly from \"&lt;a href=\"Tools%20of%20the%20Trade%20%28Diablo%20Immortal%29\"&gt;Tools of the Trade&lt;/a&gt;\", and leads directly into \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Hilts%20Trader\"&gt;The Hilts Trader&lt;/a&gt;\".\nDescription.\n\"&lt;a href=\"Wynton%27s%20Grand%20Market\"&gt;Wynton's Grand Market&lt;/a&gt; is a neutral trading ground for &lt;a href=\"adventurer\"&gt;adventurer&lt;/a&gt;s of all sorts. &lt;a href=\"Charsi\"&gt;Charsi&lt;/a&gt; suggested taking a look at their wares before visiting the other shops in the &lt;a href=\"Rakkis%20Square\"&gt;square&lt;/a&gt;.\""}
{"id": "14", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14", "title": "Trag'Oul", "text": "Trag'Oul (lit. The One Who is Forever, among other translations of the name) is an ancient and mysterious dragon-like being who guards &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt; and maintains the &lt;a href=\"Balance%20%28Philosophy%29\"&gt;Balance&lt;/a&gt; between the &lt;a href=\"High%20Heavens\"&gt;High Heavens&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=\"Burning%20Hells\"&gt;Burning Hells&lt;/a&gt;, intent on keeping Sanctuary free from &lt;a href=\"angel\"&gt;angel&lt;/a&gt;ic and &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;ic influences. His fate is tied to that of Sanctuary.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Priests%20of%20Rathma\"&gt;Priests of Rathma&lt;/a&gt; use a five-sided pattern to represent Trag'Oul, the five points each holding a symbol representing one of the five elements they believe Trag'Oul to be linked to\u2014earth, air, fire, water, and time. As the fulcrum of the Balance, they believe that the elements of Creation are tied to him.\nBiography.\nEmergence.\nTrag'Oul was born through the creation of Sanctuary itself, and as such, is tied to the mortal realm's existence. Trag'Oul was the first being to understand the &lt;a href=\"Balance%20%28Philosophy%29\"&gt;Balance&lt;/a&gt;.\nTrag'Oul entered Sanctuary for the first time just after &lt;a href=\"the%20Purge\"&gt;the Purge&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href=\"Lilith\"&gt;Lilith&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Inarius\"&gt;Inarius&lt;/a&gt;'s subsequent reactions. The dragon materialized for just a few seconds, long enough to lay the groundwork for &lt;a href=\"Linarian\"&gt;Linarian&lt;/a&gt;'s discovery of him. \nThe Student.\nLong after the Purge (at least centuries), Trag'Oul, with some hesitation, took on Linarian as a student. He taught Linarian the concept of the Balance\u2014the delicate interplay between the powers of order and chaos. Linarian eventually changed his name to \"Rathma\" (a name given to him by &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul\"&gt;Trag'Oul&lt;/a&gt;) which meant \"Keeper of the Balance,\" representing both his identity and his charge. Rathma proved himself an able student, and through Trag'Oul, received wisdom that angels and demons lacked. He began working to keep Sanctuary hidden from the High Heavens and limit the influence of the Burning Hells there. Rathma served Trag'Oul for centuries, and in doing so, kept the Balance within Sanctuary.\nThe Sin War.\nTrag'Oul tutored &lt;a href=\"Mendeln\"&gt;Mendeln&lt;/a&gt; during the &lt;a href=\"Sin%20War%20%28Event%29\"&gt;Sin War&lt;/a&gt;. He believed that war on Sanctuary could devour all of existence if left unchecked. After learning of a pact between &lt;a href=\"Inarius\"&gt;Inarius&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;, he tried to intervene, but was stopped by his fellow guardians that kept guard over worlds of their own. They warned him that interference would risk all Creation. Fortunately, the Sin War ended, and Sanctuary was spared destruction.\nAftermath.\nHaving founded the Priests of Rathma and set the Necromancers on their path, Trag'Oul vanished. He has not been seen since. The implications are dire, but the Priests of Rathma have not lost faith.\nIn-game.\nDiablo II.\nIn \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\", the Necromancer set, &lt;a href=\"Trang-Oul%27s%20Avatar\"&gt;Trang-Oul's Avatar&lt;/a&gt;, is the first mention of the dragon. Certain spells (&lt;a href=\"Bone%20Spear\"&gt;Bone Spear&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Teeth\"&gt;Teeth&lt;/a&gt;) draw upon his power.\nDiablo III.\nTrag'Oul has no presence in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\" nor its &lt;a href=\"Reaper%20of%20Souls\"&gt;expansion&lt;/a&gt;. However, there is an item named &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%20Coils\"&gt;Trag'Oul Coils&lt;/a&gt; which are legendary bracers.\nWith the introduction of the class, more items appeared: the legendary scythe, &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Corroded%20Fang\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Corroded Fang&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Avatar\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Avatar&lt;/a&gt; set.\nDiablo IV.\nDuring the Wanderer, Lorath and Neyrelle's pursuit of Elias and how to eliminate his immortality, they travelled to Hawezar where, in the depths of the swamps, they undertook a ritual to guide them to the Tree of Whispers. Under the influence of incense they could see a gigantic serpent leading them through the swamp, and in whose scales they could glimpse the future. Lorath later suggests this serpent to be the one mentioned in Rathma's prophecy, who is believed to be Trag'Oul.\nPersonality and Traits.\nThe \"&lt;a href=\"Books%20of%20Kalan\"&gt;Books of Kalan&lt;/a&gt;\" describe Trag'Oul as a celestial dragon whose body resembles a constellation of stars. In each of these stars, a different part of life is shown\u2014past, present, and future choices to be made, so one cannot see a definite future. The &lt;a href=\"Priests%20of%20Rathma\"&gt;Priests of Rathma&lt;/a&gt; believe that it is on Trag'Oul's back that the world lies, and is the closest thing the cult has to a deity. It is from Trag'Oul that Necromancers draw their power. It has also been suggested that he is a manifestation of the past, present, and future of humanity."}
{"id": "36045", "revid": "54481481", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=36045", "title": "Trag'Oul's Avatar", "text": "Trag'Oul's Avatar\u00a0is a Class\u00a0&lt;a href=\"Set\"&gt;Set&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0for s in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", obtainable at level 70. It can only drop on &lt;a href=\"Torment\"&gt;Torment&lt;/a&gt; difficulty.\nAll set pieces are restricted to Necromancers. Even &lt;a href=\"transmogrification\"&gt;transmogrification&lt;/a&gt; of these items is only available to Necromancers.\nThe set is named after &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul\"&gt;Trag'Oul&lt;/a&gt; and is themed around &lt;a href=\"Blood\"&gt;Blood&lt;/a&gt; magic and spells.\nPieces.\nThe set consists of six pieces. All six are required to complete the set, and all six are Necromancer-restricted.\nSet Bonus:\nThe first effect combines effects of all runes to the point where Blood Rush no longer costs Life, but still gets an additional charge. Moreover, despite spending no Life, it is still affected by the two other bonuses.\nThe second effect duration is refreshed every time it is applied at full Life, however, this extra Life does not change the Life cost of Blood spells (in relative values): their cost is still a percentage of the new maximum Life. It is therefore possible to use this extra Life to safely cast Blood spells. If this effect fades and any excessive Life remains, the Necromancer is simply returned to 100% Life, otherwise the same (absolute value) of Life as before fading. A buff is displayed on the panel to indicate the percentage of additional Life gained.\nThe third bonus multiplicatively boosts all skills that cost Life, including the Blood skill rune variants (prior to 2.6.1, it would also double all Life costs). It also doubles all healing from skills (including indirect sources such as minions and passives). Note that &lt;a href=\"Simulacrum\"&gt;Simulacrum&lt;/a&gt;, although it is technically a Life-spending ability, will only deal increased damage with basic attacks and Blood spells (i.e. those that would be empowered if used by the Necromancer).\nVisually, the &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Corroded%20Fang\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Corroded Fang&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Wings\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Wings&lt;/a&gt; complement this set."}
{"id": "36143", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=36143", "title": "Trag'Oul's Claws", "text": "Trag'Oul's Claws are a &lt;a href=\"gloves\"&gt;gloves&lt;/a&gt; piece of the &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Avatar\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Avatar&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Set%20Items\"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\".\nThey require character level 70 to drop, and can only drop at &lt;a href=\"Torment\"&gt;Torment&lt;/a&gt; difficulty. Only s can equip them."}
{"id": "35856", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=35856", "title": "Trag'Oul's Corroded Fang", "text": "Trag'Oul's Corroded Fang\u00a0is a &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Scythes\"&gt;scythe&lt;/a&gt; for the in\u00a0\"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It requires &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 35 to drop.\nThe unique affix makes each &lt;a href=\"Grim%20Scythe%20%28skill%29\"&gt;Cursed Scythe&lt;/a&gt; strike apply a guaranteed curse; in addition, it multiplicatively boosts all damage done by any attack against a foe with at least one curse. This bonus does not increase if the enemy suffers from more than one curse at a time. In return, it functions even if the curse was applied by another Necromancer in the party.\nThis effect is the closest equivalent of &lt;a href=\"Amplify%20Damage\"&gt;Amplify Damage&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resist\"&gt;Lower Resist&lt;/a&gt; one can get in the third game.\nVisually, this scythe matches the &lt;a href=\"Trag%27Oul%27s%20Avatar\"&gt;Trag'Oul's Avatar&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"set\"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt;."}
