{"id": "5445", "revid": "5562046", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5445", "title": "Heavenly Stone (Diablo I)", "text": "The Heavenly Stone is a quest item found in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\" needed for the quest. This quest is initiated by &lt;a href=\"Griswold\"&gt;Griswold&lt;/a&gt;, who says that the stone was stolen from a caravan by some masked thieves. It is found on a wooden pedestal on . The character will say: \"This must be what Griswold wanted\", after retrieving it.\nVarious descriptions of the stone suggest that it is actually a meteorite that fell somewhere near &lt;a href=\"Tristram\"&gt;Tristram&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "9949", "revid": "3423357", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9949", "title": "Heavenly Stone (Diablo II)", "text": "Heavenly Stones are a type of Elite class-specific &lt;a href=\"Sorceress%20Orbs\"&gt;Orbs&lt;/a&gt;, used by the &lt;a href=\"Sorceress\"&gt;Sorceress&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;. They are the Elite versions of the normal Eagle Orbs and the exceptional Glowing Orbs.\nSorceress Orbs will also receive an &lt;a href=\"Auto%20Mod%23Sorceress%20Orbs\"&gt;Auto Mod&lt;/a&gt; that can either increase her &lt;a href=\"Life\"&gt;Life&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Mana\"&gt;Mana&lt;/a&gt;.\nName Origin.\nThe Heavenly Stone, as the name implies, seems to be a piece of rock that has been fixed on a wooden shaft, as can be seen from the item graphic. It seems that \"Heavenly\" in the Diablo context can either refer to the Stronghold of Light - the &lt;a href=\"High%20Heavens\"&gt;High Heavens&lt;/a&gt;, or just random space rocks or meteorites that find its way to &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt; from the Dark Void.\nThe more magically inclined people of Sanctuary regard almost anything from the skies as brimming with high spiritual power due to its exposure to other-worldly elements during its journey in the Dark Void. As such, powerful Sorceresses may be able to channel these ley energies through these Heavenly Stones.\nThe Heavenly Stone's name also seems to have a connection with its lower counterparts, its relation to the sky - Eagle Orb and its enlightening nature - Glowing Orb. It can be assumed that the Heavenly Stone has the combined power of these two aforementioned Orbs."}
{"id": "23914", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=23914", "title": "Heavenly Strength", "text": "Heavenly Strength is a passive skill, unlocked at &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 10.\nNote that the damage debuff applies even if the Crusader wields a &lt;a href=\"one-handed\"&gt;one-handed&lt;/a&gt; weapon, or a two-handed weapon with no &lt;a href=\"shield\"&gt;shield&lt;/a&gt;, as long as this skill is selected. The debuff is not multiplicative: 20% is deducted from the \"damage increased by skills\" stat.\n&lt;a href=\"Holy%20Cause\"&gt;Holy Cause&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hellskull\"&gt;Hellskull&lt;/a&gt; can be used to negate the damage loss completely.\nSince &lt;a href=\"Flail%20of%20the%20Charge\"&gt;Flail of the Charge&lt;/a&gt; is &lt;a href=\"two-handed\"&gt;two-handed&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Norvald%27s%20Fervor\"&gt;Norvald's Fervor&lt;/a&gt; set cannot be completed without this skill, making it the only set in game that cannot be equipped by characters without a specific build option.\nDevelopment.\nOriginally, this skill also reduced the character's maximum &lt;a href=\"movement%20speed\"&gt;movement speed&lt;/a&gt;, while the &lt;a href=\"Hellskull\"&gt;Hellskull&lt;/a&gt; was removing this penalty. In Patch 2.0.5., Heavenly Strength was changed to have no negative effects, and the above-mentioned shield was changed to increase damage of &lt;a href=\"two-handed\"&gt;two-handed&lt;/a&gt; weapons instead. As of 2.1, following the two-handed weapons damage buff, the damage penalty has been bestowed upon this passive to keep the total damage roughly the same as before the patch."}
