{"id": "2207", "revid": "1687225", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2207", "title": "Hellfire Torch", "text": "The Hellfire Torch is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Items\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Charms\"&gt;Large Charm&lt;/a&gt; which is the reward for the completion of the &lt;a href=\"Pandemonium%20Event\"&gt;Pandemonium Event&lt;/a&gt;. Only one may be in the &lt;a href=\"inventory\"&gt;inventory&lt;/a&gt; at a time. The wide variation of possible rolled stats, along with the fact that it adds +3 a random class's skills instead of +all skills, means that perfect hellfire torches for specific characters usually requires multiple Uber Tristram runs and are therefore highly sought after, especially early in the Ladder. Even badly rolled hellfire torches offer far more stats, resistances and skills than any magical charm per unit of space.\nStats.\nRequired Level: 75\nDiablo III.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;'s equivalent of the Pandemonium Event (&lt;a href=\"Infernal%20Machine\"&gt;Infernal Machine&lt;/a&gt;), player characters can obtain &lt;a href=\"Hellfire%20Ring\"&gt;Hellfire Ring&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Hellfire%20Amulet\"&gt;Hellfire Amulet&lt;/a&gt;, two unique pieces of jewellery inspired by Hellfire Torch. Both grant bonuses to stats, and the former one fire-based procs as well."}
{"id": "1674", "revid": "3565990", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=1674", "title": "Hellfire quests", "text": "In Diablo I, the quests are a series of missions (fewer in multi-player) on which the character is sent, and which offer advantages when completed. None of them need to be completed, but all add background detail and most give valuable rewards (even if only when reselling)."}
{"id": "2434", "revid": "50366882", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2434", "title": "Hellforge", "text": "The Hellforge is located in the &lt;a href=\"Burning%20Hells\"&gt;Burning Hells&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe Hellforge is a magical forge found in the deepest pit of the &lt;a href=\"Realm%20of%20Destruction\"&gt;Realm of Destruction&lt;/a&gt;\u2014the realm's sole source of creation, yet devoted to the forging of weapons that would only be used to destroy, of note amongst them is the &lt;a href=\"Desolation%20Cannon\"&gt;Desolation Cannon&lt;/a&gt;. The Hellforge holds many anvils where Hell's most powerful weapons were created, among them the &lt;a href=\"Anvil%20of%20Annihilation\"&gt;Anvil of Annihilation&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Hephasto\"&gt;Hephasto&lt;/a&gt; oversaw (or at least worked in) the forge. He would twist &lt;a href=\"soul\"&gt;soul&lt;/a&gt;s to use as catalysts in the forge, and the remaining coals carried the mark of their torment. &lt;a href=\"Gishtur\"&gt;Gishtur&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Beledwe\"&gt;Beledwe&lt;/a&gt; also worked at the forge.\nHistory.\nDuring the &lt;a href=\"Great%20Conflict\"&gt;Great Conflict&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"archangel\"&gt;archangel&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Izual\"&gt;Izual&lt;/a&gt; led an assault on the Hellforge, in an attempt to prevent the creation of the &lt;a href=\"demonblade\"&gt;demonblade&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Shadowfang\"&gt;Shadowfang&lt;/a&gt;. However, he was overcome by the &lt;a href=\"Demonic%20Legion\"&gt;demonic legions&lt;/a&gt;.\nLong after Izual's fall, a &lt;a href=\"Classes%23Diablo%20II\"&gt;group of heroes&lt;/a&gt; made their own assault on the Hellforge. It was their intent to use the Anvil of Annihilation to destroy &lt;a href=\"Mephisto\"&gt;Mephisto&lt;/a&gt;'s &lt;a href=\"soulstone\"&gt;soulstone&lt;/a&gt; and after retrieving it, &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;'s as well. In both counts they were successful, and the soulstones were destroyed and their contained spirits supposedly banished to the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Abyss\"&gt;Black Abyss&lt;/a&gt;. They were the first mortals to have ever entered the Hellforge.\nGame Effect.\nThe Hellforge appears in &lt;a href=\"The%20Harrowing\"&gt;Act IV&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" and is protected by an &lt;a href=\"Overlord%20%28Diablo%20I%29\"&gt;Overlord&lt;/a&gt; called &lt;a href=\"Hephasto%20the%20Armorer\"&gt;Hephasto the Armorer&lt;/a&gt;, who holds the &lt;a href=\"Hellforge%20Hammer\"&gt;Hellforge Hammer&lt;/a&gt; required to smash the Soulstone. During &lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;, your hero completes a quest named &lt;a href=\"Mephisto%27s%20Soulstone%20%28quest%29\"&gt;Mephisto's Soulstone&lt;/a&gt;, where he/she smashes Mephisto's soulstone using the Hellforge and the Hammer.\nHowever, you do not need to have Mephisto's soulstone in your personal inventory. Either this may be a bug, or somehow, &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt;'s magic allows him to &lt;a href=\"teleport\"&gt;teleport&lt;/a&gt; the soulstone directly to the Hellforge when you are there and ready to use it. All you really need is to wield the &lt;a href=\"Hellforge%20Hammer\"&gt;Hellforge Hammer&lt;/a&gt;, and whether it's on your inventory or in your &lt;a href=\"stash\"&gt;stash&lt;/a&gt;, you will still be able to complete the soulstone-smashing &lt;a href=\"quests\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt; with it. Nevertheless, the soulstone is found to have vanished once you reopen your Stash.\nWhen the soulstone is destroyed it gives several perfect and flawless gems as well as a potentially high-level rune. It is common to offer the reward for characters' Hellforge quest in exchange for a &lt;a href=\"rush\"&gt;rush&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe possible runes vary by difficulty:\nNote that each possible rune has an equal chance to drop (1:11), meaning the odds you'll get a Gul in Hell difficulty are exactly the same as the odds you'll only get a Hel."}
