{"id": "50619", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=50619", "title": "Khamsin Edge (Lore)", "text": "Khamsin Edge are tribal &lt;a href=\"Warrior\"&gt;Warrior&lt;/a&gt;s who protect the desert oases of &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;Kehjistan&lt;/a&gt;. Once many in number, now few remain to protect their charges. By &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231336\"&gt;1336&lt;/a&gt;, Khamsin Edge only had enough strength to support safe travel between &lt;a href=\"Alcarnus\"&gt;Alcarnus&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dahlgur%20Oasis\"&gt;Dahlgur&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "31648", "revid": "154566", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31648", "title": "Khanduran Rune", "text": "The Khanduran Rune is a &lt;a href=\"crafting%20material\"&gt;crafting material&lt;/a&gt; in \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", added in Patch 2.3.0.\nIt is used with &lt;a href=\"Kanai%27s%20Cube\"&gt;Kanai's Cube&lt;/a&gt; and at the Blacksmith for various recipes of &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;legendary&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Set%20Items\"&gt;set&lt;/a&gt; items. This material is obtained from a &lt;a href=\"Horadric%20Cache\"&gt;Horadric Cache&lt;/a&gt; given by &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt; for completion of &lt;a href=\"bounty\"&gt;bounties&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Adventure%20Mode\"&gt;Adventure Mode&lt;/a&gt;."}
{"id": "2119", "revid": "46014304", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=2119", "title": "Khanduras", "text": "Khanduras was one of the &lt;a href=\"Western%20Kingdoms\"&gt;Western Kingdoms&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Sanctuary\"&gt;Sanctuary&lt;/a&gt;. \nLore.\nKhanduras is bordered by &lt;a href=\"Westmarch\"&gt;Westmarch&lt;/a&gt; and its &lt;a href=\"Gulf%20of%20Westmarch\"&gt;Gulf&lt;/a&gt; to the west, the &lt;a href=\"Sharval%20Wilds\"&gt;Sharval Wilds&lt;/a&gt; to the north, and is separated from &lt;a href=\"Aranoch\"&gt;Aranoch&lt;/a&gt; by the &lt;a href=\"Tamoe%20Mountain%20Range\"&gt;Tamoe Mountain Range&lt;/a&gt;. Khanduras is best known for the events surrounding &lt;a href=\"Diablo\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;'s return and the darkening of &lt;a href=\"Tristram\"&gt;Tristram&lt;/a&gt;. Compared to Westmarch, Khanduras has always been poorer than its neighbor, which has long been a point of resentment.\nThe north of Khanduras is a land of swamps and fens. There were once many castles in the land, but over time, they fell into ruin, absorbed by trees and the earth itself (the family of &lt;a href=\"the%20Countess\"&gt;the Countess&lt;/a&gt; was the last noble family left in the region, before their fall). The crofters who remained lived in poverty, getting very little out of the north\u2019s sticky, muddy, icy soil. Most made charcoal, selling it to places as far abroad as &lt;a href=\"Ivgorod\"&gt;Ivgorod&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Lut%20Gholein\"&gt;Lut Gholein&lt;/a&gt;, though were paid little for it. &lt;a href=\"Swamp%20oil\"&gt;Swamp oil&lt;/a&gt; was another resource which was sold abroad. Some gained coin by leading travelers through the bogs and dangers.\nDespite the poverty of the marsh, the northerners were proud that they could live in their own fashion, where the people of the south of Khanduras feared to tread.\n&lt;a href=\"Hallow%27s%20Wake\"&gt;Hallow's Wake&lt;/a&gt; is celebrated in Khanduras.\nHistory.\nEarly History.\nThere is circumstantial evidence that Khanduras was populated by &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt;s by the 7th century.\nYears after the last of the &lt;a href=\"Horadrim\"&gt;Horadrim&lt;/a&gt; had died, a great and prosperous society grew in the lands of the West. As time wore on, many Eastern pilgrims settled in the lands surrounding Khanduras and soon established small, self-contained kingdoms. A few of these kingdoms bickered with Khanduras over holdings of property or routes of trade. These squabbles did little to upset the lasting peace of the West, and the kingdom of Westmarch proved to be a strong ally of Khanduras as the two lands steadily engaged in ventures of barter and commerce. However, relations were strained, as Westmarch was much wealthier than Khanduras. Many bandits operating from Khanduras raided Westmarch, and &lt;a href=\"Torion\"&gt;some&lt;/a&gt; suspected that some of their ill-gotten gains ended up in Khanduras's coffers. However, this was never proven.\nDuring Khanduras's long range of peace, most towns and cities agreed upon a standard &lt;a href=\"gold\"&gt;gold&lt;/a&gt; coin to use in trade. The garb of those who rule in Khanduras grew more ornate with each generation.\nDuring this time, a bold, new religion of the &lt;a href=\"Light\"&gt;Light&lt;/a&gt; known as &lt;a href=\"Zakarum\"&gt;Zakarum&lt;/a&gt; began to spread throughout the kingdom of Westmarch and into many of its northern principalities. Zakarum, founded in the Far East, implored followers to enter into the Light and forsake the darkness that lurked within their souls. The people of Westmarch adopted the statutes of Zakarum as their sacred mission in the world. Westmarch began to turn towards its neighbors, expecting them to embrace this new beginning as well. Tensions rose between the kingdoms of Westmarch and Khanduras as the priests of Zakarum began to preach their foreign dogma whether they were welcomed or not.\nIt was in &lt;a href=\"Timeline%231258\"&gt;1258&lt;/a&gt; then that &lt;a href=\"Leoric\"&gt;Leoric&lt;/a&gt; came unto the lands of Khanduras and, in the name of Zakarum, declared himself king. Leoric was a deeply religious man and had brought many knights and priests with him that comprised his &lt;a href=\"Order%20of%20the%20Light\"&gt;Order of the Light&lt;/a&gt;. Leoric and his trusted advisor, the &lt;a href=\"Archbishop%20Lazarus\"&gt;Archbishop Lazarus&lt;/a&gt;, made their way to the city of Tristram. Leoric appropriated the ancient, decrepit &lt;a href=\"Tristram%20Cathedral\"&gt;monastery&lt;/a&gt; on the outskirts of the town for his seat of power and renovated it to match its time-lost glory. Although the free people of Khanduras were not pleased with being placed under the sudden rule of a foreign King, Leoric served them with justice and might. Eventually, the people of Khanduras grew to respect the kind Leoric, sensing that he sought only to guide and protect them against the oppression of darkness.\nThe Awakening.\nWhat Leoric didn't know was that his throne of power was right above where Diablo, Lord of Terror, had been sealed by the Horadrim centuries ago. After being freed by Lazarus, the &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt; chose Leoric as his mortal host. Leoric kept this a secret, convinced that his piety would allow him to overcome the ordeal, but nonetheless, Diablo was able to influence the king's behavior. His rule became increasingly tyrannical, and the people took to calling him \"the Black King.\" Lazarus, who was secretly in league with Diablo, attempted to remove Leoric's closest allies by convincing the king that Westmarch was plotting against him. The paranoid monarch thus ordered that his armies march on Westmarch and his advisors be sent as \"emissaries.\" It was a war that no-one in Khanduras wanted, but nonetheless, his armies were bound to serve their king and marched to battle.\nThe outcome was a boon for the demon lord. Khanduras's army was torn apart by Westmarch's superior numbers and defensive positions. In Tristram, Leoric was left with no-one, his &lt;a href=\"Asylla\"&gt;wife&lt;/a&gt; dead by his own deranged orders, his &lt;a href=\"Aidan\"&gt;elder son&lt;/a&gt; gone with the army, and his &lt;a href=\"Albrecht\"&gt;younger son&lt;/a&gt; now Diablo's host. The knight &lt;a href=\"Lachdanan\"&gt;Lachdanan&lt;/a&gt;, having returned from the disastorous war, confronted his king. Beyond salvation, Leoric fell to Lachdanan's blade.\nThus, Khanduras was left without a ruler. Darkness came to Tristram and the surrounding countryside, with Diablo unleashing his demons upon the land. Eventually, Diablo was defeated, by a returned Aidan, along with two &lt;a href=\"Blood%20Raven\"&gt;other&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"The%20Summoner\"&gt;heroes&lt;/a&gt;. Yet the cost included Albrecht's life, and after attempting to bind the &lt;a href=\"Prime%20Evil\"&gt;Prime Evil&lt;/a&gt; within himself, Aidan's soul.\nReturning Light, Returning Darkness.\nDiablo's acts had a foul legacy on Khanduras\u2014his journey to the east left Tristram destroyed in his wake, the &lt;a href=\"Sisters%20of%20the%20Sightless%20Eye\"&gt;Sisters of the Sightless Eye&lt;/a&gt; temporarily lost their &lt;a href=\"Eastgate\"&gt;monastery&lt;/a&gt;, and demons and &lt;a href=\"khazra\"&gt;khazra&lt;/a&gt; roamed the countryside. Yet in the years following the defeat of the Prime Evils, merchants slowly began to return to the region, looking to profit from adventurers who plumbed the depths of the Tristram Cathedral. The town of &lt;a href=\"New%20Tristram\"&gt;New Tristram&lt;/a&gt; arose, but fell into decline.\nTwenty years after the defeat of &lt;a href=\"Baal\"&gt;Baal&lt;/a&gt; at &lt;a href=\"Mount%20Arreat\"&gt;Mount Arreat&lt;/a&gt;, evil once again touched Khanduras. The &lt;a href=\"Coven\"&gt;Coven&lt;/a&gt; had infiltrated the region, and with the fall of &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Tyrael&lt;/a&gt; from the &lt;a href=\"High%20Heavens\"&gt;High Heavens&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;dead&lt;/a&gt; themselves rose to attack the living. Ultimately, New Tristram and the surrounding countryside were saved, but not without cost to its people. Months afterwards, roving packs of demons can be found roaming Khanduras.\nCowpocalypse.\nAround this time, rumors spread through &lt;a href=\"Khanduras\"&gt;Khanduras&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Infernal%20Bovine\"&gt;bipedal bovines&lt;/a&gt; overruning various townships throughout the country. Artistic renderings of these creatures were placed in various inns. One terrified farmer even referred to this surge of sightings as the \"Cowpocalypse.\" The sightings were decried as a hoax, but citizens were issued an advisory to stay clear of the wilds, and not enter any strange portals that may or may not lead to &lt;a href=\"Not%20the%20Cow%20Level\"&gt;alternate planes of existence&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nKhanduras has featured in almost every \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20series\"&gt;Diablo&lt;/a&gt;\" game. In \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20I\"&gt;Diablo I&lt;/a&gt;\", the player is confined to Tristram, while it forms the basis of the first &lt;a href=\"act\"&gt;act&lt;/a&gt; of both \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20II\"&gt;Diablo II&lt;/a&gt;\" and \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;III&lt;/a&gt;\". In \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20Immortal\"&gt;Diablo Immortal&lt;/a&gt;\", Khanduras is explored in the &lt;a href=\"Wortham\"&gt;Wortham&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Dark%20Wood\"&gt;Dark Wood&lt;/a&gt; zones. \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20IV\"&gt;Diablo IV&lt;/a&gt;\" will be the first game where Khanduras is not explorable."}
{"id": "31764", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=31764", "title": "Kharazim", "text": "Kharazim is a male &lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt;.\nHe keeps his hair shaven out of piety.\nBiography.\nKharazim was born under the sign of &lt;a href=\"Ytar\"&gt;Ytar&lt;/a&gt;. Becoming a &lt;a href=\"Monk%20of%20Ivgorod\"&gt;Monk of Ivgorod&lt;/a&gt;, Kharazim apparently adopted him as his patron deity. He never knew his family.\nAs a servant to the &lt;a href=\"Patriarchs\"&gt;Patriarchs&lt;/a&gt;, Kharazim travelled across many lands (not including &lt;a href=\"Kehjistan\"&gt;Kehjistan&lt;/a&gt;) and met many people. For the people he met, he commented that \"wisdom is as rare as a jewel nestled in a mountain peak.\" \nWith the coming of the &lt;a href=\"Tyrael\"&gt;Fallen Star&lt;/a&gt;, Kharazim journeyed to &lt;a href=\"New%20Tristram\"&gt;New Tristram&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn-game.\nDiablo III.\nKharazim uses the appearance of the Monk from \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\", and can be considered a canonical portrayal.\nHeroes of the Storm.\nKharazim appears as a Monk hero in \"&lt;a href=\"Heroes%20of%20the%20Storm\"&gt;Heroes of the Storm&lt;/a&gt;\", and may be considered a possible representation of &lt;a href=\"the%20Nephalem\"&gt;the Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; in a similar manner to characters such as &lt;a href=\"Johanna\"&gt;Johanna&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Valla\"&gt;Valla&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Sonya\"&gt;Sonya&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Nazeebo\"&gt;Nazeebo&lt;/a&gt;.\nHe bears standard Monk equipment: full tier of (with respective armor tier components), fighting unarmed. He uses skills from Diablo III, namely &lt;a href=\"Dashing%20Strike\"&gt;Dashing Strike&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Seven-Sided%20Strike\"&gt;Seven-Sided Strike&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Breath%20of%20Heaven\"&gt;Breath of Heaven&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Serenity\"&gt;Serenity&lt;/a&gt; and so-called Combo Attack (closely resembles &lt;a href=\"Way%20of%20the%20Hundred%20Fists\"&gt;Way of the Hundred Fists&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Deadly%20Reach\"&gt;Deadly Reach&lt;/a&gt;).\nUnlike other classes, he can choose his passive trait before the combat begins (but may not change it afterwards): Iron Fists to gain bonus attack damage, &lt;a href=\"Transcendence%20%28Monk%29\"&gt;Transcendence&lt;/a&gt; to heal himself through melee combat, or Insight to restore mana and find a balance between both offensive and defensive roles."}
{"id": "19488", "revid": "58609", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=19488", "title": "Khasim Outpost", "text": "The Khasim Outpost is a location in &lt;a href=\"Act%20II%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Act II&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It is located near the &lt;a href=\"Black%20Canyon%20Bridge\"&gt;Black Canyon Bridge&lt;/a&gt;, and across from the entrance to the &lt;a href=\"Stinging%20Winds\"&gt;Stinging Winds&lt;/a&gt;.\nLore.\nThe &lt;a href=\"town\"&gt;town&lt;/a&gt; was originally protected by the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Wolves\"&gt;Iron Wolves&lt;/a&gt;, before they were supplanted by the &lt;a href=\"Imperial%20Guard\"&gt;Imperial Guard&lt;/a&gt;. Reportedly, the people in the town were growing restless, and the Guard were sent in to secure it. Whatever the truth of that matter, in reality, the Guard were &lt;a href=\"Deceiver\"&gt;Deceiver&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"demon\"&gt;demon&lt;/a&gt;s in service to &lt;a href=\"Belial\"&gt;Belial&lt;/a&gt;. The Iron Wolves were held captive, planned to be sacrificed to Belial.\nBelial himself ordered &lt;a href=\"Maghda\"&gt;Maghda&lt;/a&gt; to set a trap for &lt;a href=\"The%20Nephalem\"&gt;The Nephalem&lt;/a&gt; at the outpost. Due to the road to &lt;a href=\"Alcarnus\"&gt;Alcarnus&lt;/a&gt; being blocked, The Nephalem had to divert to the outpost on their journey. The Nephalem arrived, but was able to free the Iron Wolves and defeat the demons.\nIn-game.\nThe Outpost features in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Road%20to%20Alcarnus\"&gt;The Road to Alcarnus&lt;/a&gt;\" &lt;a href=\"quest\"&gt;quest&lt;/a&gt; in Act I."}
{"id": "34568", "revid": "25771421", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=34568", "title": "Khassett's Cord of Righteousness", "text": "Khassett's Cord of Righteousness\u00a0is a &lt;a href=\"Legendary%20Items\"&gt;Legendary&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"belts\"&gt;belt&lt;/a&gt; implemented in patch 2.4.2 of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It\u00a0requires &lt;a href=\"character%20level\"&gt;character level&lt;/a&gt; 70 to drop.\nThe unique affix effects are both multiplicative to all other modifiers, and not added to the respective stats.\nDevelopment.\nOriginally (on the earliest stages of development), this item had a placeholder description: \" \"Lo, on the forth day the great one said, 'Let there be Crusader buffs.' and there were.\"\"\nThough it shares graphics with &lt;a href=\"Sebor%27s%20Nightmare\"&gt;Sebor's Nightmare&lt;/a&gt;, it did not replace the latter in game."}
{"id": "28930", "revid": "1773829", "url": "https://diablo.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28930", "title": "Khatun", "text": "Khatun, Sky Terror is a &lt;a href=\"Unique%20Monsters\"&gt;unique&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Armored%20Destroyer\"&gt;Armored Destroyer&lt;/a&gt; in &lt;a href=\"Act%20IV%20%28Diablo%20III%29\"&gt;Act IV&lt;/a&gt; of \"&lt;a href=\"Diablo%20III\"&gt;Diablo III&lt;/a&gt;\". It is found in the &lt;a href=\"Gardens%20of%20Hope\"&gt;Gardens of Hope&lt;/a&gt; 1st Tier, usually immediately to the north of the entrance.\nIn combat, it has &lt;a href=\"Molten\"&gt;Molten&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Mortar\"&gt;Mortar&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Teleporter\"&gt;Teleporter&lt;/a&gt; traits. Unlike most other Destroyers, when approached it will already be waiting on the ground, rather than dropping from the sky.\nTrivia.\n\"Khatun\" is a female equivalent of the \"Khan\" title.\nThere is also a \"World of Warcraft\" Old God named C'Thun (pronounced \"Ka-Thune\")."}
